-- в”Ђв”Ђ Robin AI в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Robin AI was a London-based AI-powered contract review and legal intelligence platform; the company wound down as an independent business in late 2025, with its managed services team acquired by Scissero and its technology and engineering team absorbed by Microsoft in January 2026.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Historically freemium with paid subscription and custom enterprise tiers; no longer independently sold as of 2026$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE(NULL, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2019, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Approximately 100-150 employees at peak (2024-2025); company wound down as an independent business in late 2025/early 2026$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$London, England, United Kingdom (historical)$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Robin AI 2026 Status: What Happened to the Legal Contract AI Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Robin AI was an AI-powered contract review platform that wound down in late 2025. Learn its history, features, pricing, and what happened to the company.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Robin AI was a London-based, AI-powered contract review and negotiation platform founded in 2019 by Richard Robinson, a former disputes lawyer at Clifford Chance, and James Clough, a machine learning researcher trained at Imperial College London, with headquarters at 10 Devonshire Square in London. The company combined proprietary legal AI models with a human-in-the-loop team of in-house lawyers to help corporate legal and procurement teams review, redline, and negotiate contracts faster, and at its peak reportedly served 13 Fortune 500 companies with around $10 million in annual recurring revenue and a further $16 million sales pipeline. Robin AI raised significant venture funding over its life, including a $26 million round highlighted in a 2024 press release, and was recognized on startup lists such as the UK's Startups 100 in 2025. However, in the second half of 2025 the company's multi-year losses outpaced its revenue growth, and after failing to close a planned $50 million funding round in October 2025, Robin AI laid off roughly one-third of its staff (about 50 roles) and entered a winding-up process and receivership. As a result of this collapse, Robin AI's assets were split and sold in two separate deals in late 2025 and early 2026: its managed services arm, the human-in-the-loop contract review business with around 75 staff, was acquired by the AI-forward law firm Scissero in December 2025, while Microsoft acquired (acqui-hired) Robin AI's technology and engineering team in January 2026 to strengthen legal AI capabilities inside Microsoft Word and its broader productivity suite. Because of this, as of mid-2026 Robin AI no longer operates as an independent, purchasable SaaS product or company; its historical offering combined a freemium tier with paid subscriptions and custom enterprise plans (including API access, advanced integrations, SSO, and SLAs), but exact historical pricing was never fully publicized, and prospective buyers today would instead need to evaluate Scissero (for managed contract review services) or watch for Robin AI's underlying technology resurfacing inside Microsoft's products rather than seeking to purchase 'Robin AI' directly. This makes Robin AI a useful case study in AI-legal-tech startup economics: strong enterprise logos and real revenue were not sufficient to sustain the company through a difficult fundraising environment for applied legal AI.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'fb49326f-7c73-43d6-b58a-39f713485eed';

